I deployed my site to Cloudflare Pages. Took about 10 minutes.

Then I opened a blog post. The Turnstile captcha on my comment form? Gone. Invisible. Like it was never there.

I went to `/keystatic`, my CMS. It loaded. No login screen. No authentication. Anyone on the internet could see it. And when I clicked into a collection, it broke. "Unable to load collection. Unexpected token."

Two features. Both broken. Both worked perfectly on localhost.

Here's every gotcha I hit going from `npm run dev` to a live site on Cloudflare Pages. And how to avoid all of them.

## Connecting GitHub to Cloudflare Pages

This part is easy. Almost suspiciously easy.

Go to the Cloudflare dashboard. Workers & Pages. Create. Pages. Connect to Git. Pick your repo.

Build settings:
- Framework preset: **Astro**
- Build command: `npm run build`
- Build output directory: `dist`

Click Deploy.

That's it. Every push to `main` triggers a new build. Your site goes live in about 30 seconds.

If you want to test a one-off deploy without connecting GitHub, you can use the CLI instead:

```
npm run build
npx wrangler pages deploy dist --project-name your-project-name
```

You'll need `npx wrangler login` first. But the GitHub method is better for anything you plan to maintain.

## Your wrangler.jsonc Has Secrets in It

This one almost got me.

My `wrangler.jsonc` has the Cloudflare D1 database ID in it. That's not something you want sitting in a public repo.

Here's what the file looks like:

```json
{
  "d1_databases": [{
    "binding": "DB",
    "database_name": "aristotle-comments",
    "database_id": "fef37378-f971-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx"
  }]
}
```

That database ID is tied to your Cloudflare account. Not the kind of thing you push to GitHub.

The fix takes three commands:

```bash
# Stop tracking the file in git (doesn't delete it locally)
git rm --cached wrangler.jsonc

# Add it to .gitignore
echo "wrangler.jsonc" >> .gitignore

# Commit
git add .gitignore && git commit -m "gitignore wrangler.jsonc"
```

The `git rm --cached` part confused me at first. Git shows "deleted: wrangler.jsonc" and it looks like your file is gone. It's not. The file is still on your machine. Git just stops tracking it. Future commits won't include it.

If you haven't created your D1 database yet, run this first:

```bash
npx wrangler d1 create your-database-name
```

It gives you the database ID. Paste that into your `wrangler.jsonc`. Then gitignore the file before you push.

## Secret vs Text in the Cloudflare Dashboard

When you add environment variables in Cloudflare Pages, you get two options: **Secret** and **Text**.

Simple rule. If it shows up in your HTML (the browser can see it anyway), use Text. Everything else is Secret.

For my setup:

| Variable | Type | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `PUBLIC_TURNSTILE_SITE_KEY` | Text | It's in the HTML. Browsers need it. |
| `TURNSTILE_SECRET_KEY` | Secret | Server-side only. Verifies captcha responses. |
| `ADMIN_SECRET` | Secret | Admin password. Obviously. |
| `IP_HASH_SALT` | Secret | Used to hash IPs for rate limiting. |

For the `IP_HASH_SALT`, don't reuse whatever you had in your `.dev.vars` file. Generate a fresh one for production:

```bash
openssl rand -base64 32
```

Copy the output. Paste it as the value. Done.

One thing that tripped me up. After you add all your variables and hit save, they don't apply to your current deployment. You need to trigger a new build. Either push a commit or click "Retry deployment" in the Cloudflare dashboard.

This sounds obvious. It wasn't obvious to me at the time.

## Why My Turnstile Captcha Was Invisible

This was the big one. And it took me a while to figure out.

My blog posts use `export const prerender = true` in Astro. That means they're built as static HTML at build time. Not generated on each request.

Here's the problem. The Turnstile site key is read from an environment variable:

```js
const turnstileSiteKey = import.meta.env.PUBLIC_TURNSTILE_SITE_KEY || '';
```

When `prerender = true`, this code runs during the build. Not when someone visits the page. So the value of `PUBLIC_TURNSTILE_SITE_KEY` has to exist when Cloudflare builds your site.

I deployed first. Added env vars after. Turnstile never saw the key.

The HTML had `data-sitekey=""`. Empty string. Turnstile looked at that and said "nothing to do here." No error. No warning. Just silently missing.

**The fix:** add your `PUBLIC_` env vars in Cloudflare *before* you deploy. Or if you already deployed, just redeploy after adding them.

This applies to any `PUBLIC_` variable on a prerendered page. If it's empty during the build, it's empty forever on that deployment.

## Keystatic Broke the Moment I Went Live

On localhost, Keystatic is great. Clean CMS interface at `/keystatic`. Edit blog posts, manage projects, all through a browser.

Then I went to `aristotle.me/keystatic` on production.

Two problems.

**First, no authentication.** The dashboard just opened. No login. No password. Nothing. Anyone with the URL could see my CMS. That's a security issue.

**Second, it crashed.** I clicked "Blog Posts" and got: "Unable to load collection. Unexpected token 'T', 'The Keysta...' is not valid JSON."

Both problems have the same root cause. My Keystatic config was set to `storage: { kind: 'local' }`. That means it reads and writes directly to the filesystem. On your laptop, that's your project folder. On Cloudflare Pages, there is no filesystem. There's nothing to read from.

You have two options.

**Option 1: GitHub storage.** Change the storage to `kind: 'github'` for production. Keystatic reads and writes through the GitHub API. This also adds GitHub OAuth for authentication. Nobody gets in without a GitHub login.

This requires creating a GitHub OAuth app and setting up three more env vars (`KEYSTATIC_GITHUB_CLIENT_ID`, `KEYSTATIC_GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET`, `KEYSTATIC_SECRET`). Works well but adds complexity.

**Option 2: Local only.** If you write posts from your terminal anyway (like I do with Claude Code), you might not need a production CMS at all.

I went with option 2. Here's the change in `astro.config.mjs`:

```js
const isDev = process.env.NODE_ENV !== 'production';

export default defineConfig({
  integrations: [
    // ...other integrations
    ...(isDev ? [keystatic()] : []),
  ],
});
```

Keystatic loads in dev mode. In production, it's completely gone. `/keystatic` returns a 404. No CMS to break into. No orphaned routes.

If you use Keystatic from a browser regularly, go with option 1. If your content workflow is terminal-first, option 2 is cleaner.

## The Full Deploy Checklist

Here's what I wish I had before I started. Everything in one place.

**Before your first deploy:**
1. Create your D1 database with `wrangler d1 create`
2. Update `wrangler.jsonc` with the real database ID
3. Add `wrangler.jsonc` to `.gitignore` and `git rm --cached` it
4. Add all env vars in Cloudflare Pages settings (both Secret and Text)
5. Decide on Keystatic: GitHub storage or local-only
6. Push to GitHub

**After your first deploy:**
1. Check every page that uses a `PUBLIC_` env var
2. Verify Turnstile shows up on comment forms
3. Try visiting `/keystatic` to confirm it's either authenticated or 404
4. Open DevTools, check for console errors
5. If anything's wrong, fix it and redeploy. Env vars only apply to new builds.

**Variables you'll need in Cloudflare:**

| Variable | Type |
|---|---|
| `PUBLIC_TURNSTILE_SITE_KEY` | Text |
| `TURNSTILE_SECRET_KEY` | Secret |
| `ADMIN_SECRET` | Secret |
| `IP_HASH_SALT` | Secret (fresh random value) |

The deploy itself takes 10 minutes. The gotchas take an hour if you don't know about them.

Now you know about them.
